{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_28","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc 'tail -n 40 human-intervention-logs/org.glassfish.web:javax.el:2.2.4/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-03T17-41-27-363908Z.log'","aggregated_output":"[thinking] \n[thinking] I need to avoid using deprecated APIs, and there's a potential issue with `MethodExpression.isParametersProvided` being misspelled. It's important not to introduce new deprecated elements. I’m thinking about whether we need to use direct reflection, especially since the custom ELResolver may have a package-private constructor. \n[thinking] \n[thinking] There’s also a concern regarding how `getType` in `RootObjectELResolver` returns `Object.class`, which might coerce types unexpectedly. There are a few other conditions to analyze, but overall, I’m not sure we need to add comments to the code. Summarizing the existing test coverage should be enough.\n[thinking] \n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[assistant-event] text_start\n[assistant] Implemented a new test in:\n[assistant] \n[assistant] `tests/src/org.glassfish.web/javax.el/2.2.4/src/test/java/org_glassfish_web/javax_el/Javax_elTest.java`\n[assistant] \n[assistant] What existing coverage already included:\n[assistant] - ExpressionFactory arithmetic, composite expressions, functions, and variables\n[assistant] - Conditional/logical/empty operators\n[assistant] - Nested collection read/write and `ValueReference`\n[assistant] - Method expressions and method metadata\n[assistant] - Standard resolvers for maps, lists, arrays, resource bundles, and beans\n[assistant] - Composite resolver ordering\n[assistant] - Type coercion and literal value expressions\n[assistant] \n[assistant] New feature covered:\n[assistant] - Resolution of top-level implicit/root objects through a custom public `ELResolver`, including:\n[assistant]   - Reading an implicit object without using `VariableMapper`\n[assistant]   - Navigating into that object via `MapELResolver`\n[assistant]   - Writing nested values\n[assistant]   - Writing top-level root values through the resolver\n[assistant] \n[assistant] No existing test logic was changed. I did not run tests, per instruction.\n[assistant-event] text_end\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Checking Checkstyle issues**\\n\\nI need to check a possible issue with Checkstyle about whether a public nested class constructor should indeed be public. The existing constructor is package-private, which seems fine, but there are dynamic-access rules to consider. The user only asks about modifying one file, so I might just add a helper public class that's inner. \\n\\nThere's also a thought about whether we can strengthen the test to include locale features, but I’m hesitant to add too much complexity. The current test uses a custom resolver already.\\n\\n**Considering API concerns**\\n\\nI need to avoid using deprecated APIs, and there's a potential issue with `MethodExpression.isParametersProvided` being misspelled. It's important not to introduce new deprecated elements. I’m thinking about whether we need to use direct reflection, especially since the custom ELResolver may have a package-private constructor. \\n\\nThere’s also a concern regarding how `getType` in `RootObjectELResolver` returns `Object.class`, which might coerce types unexpectedly. There are a few other conditions to analyze, but overall, I’m not sure we need to add comments to the code. Summarizing the existing test coverage should be enough.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_09d7fa4b6dcb3b3a0169f788bcd6bc8197b4501f5281654be9\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp94jGmNknmqrV54X_e-nZqWxaueiWYAf5IRkoyWZ6bANzESIIJmDN1w6PWuc7JFcRe_JImR-cQaA1tCohL9IrfWQSVVwxciJGzuKgciACIRHLrrojmLb6qG8PgM29V-4iQM7TXgQs0E-NHDNJP7JktWjmSHke4smtCrcv8jMI0thpqmpGKgOV-j2NQwOKGlI4YFa3_eSZzgo-3XoJSg7-UajL